olive oil
1 Carrot
1 Onion
3 clove Garlic
1 packet Beef Mince
1 packet Tomato Paste
1 sachet Middle Eastern Seasoning
1 packet Currants
¼ cup water
1 packet filo pastry
1 packet Greek-Style Yoghurt
1 packet Mixed Salad Leaves
drizzle vinegar (balsamic or white wine)

• Preheat oven to 220°C/200°C fan-forced.
• Grate carrot.
• Finely chop onion and garlic.

• Heat a large frying pan over high heat with a drizzle of olive oil. Cook beef mince and onion, breaking up with a spoon, until just browned, 4-5 minutes.
• Add tomato paste, Middle Eastern seasoning, currants and half the garlic, then cook until fragrant, 1-2 minutes.
• Reduce heat to medium, then add the water, then simmer until slightly reduced, 2-3 minutes. Season with salt and pepper. Remove from heat.

TIP: Add a splash of water if the filling looks dry.

• Lay a filo pastry sheet on a dry surface and brush with olive oil. Top with another filo sheet. Repeat with remaining sheets to make 2 stacks (you'll have 1 sheet of filo left over!).
• Divide beef filling mixture along the long edge of the filo stacks. Roll the filo to enclose filling, making 2 logs.
• Place a log on a lined oven tray and curl to form a snail. Repeat with remaining filo log.
• Brush with olive oil and bake for 20 minutes, until golden and crisp.

• Meanwhile, wipe out frying pan and return to medium-high heat with a drizzle of olive oil. Cook remaining garlic until fragrant, 1 minute.
• Transfer garlic oil to a small bowl, then add Greek-style yoghurt and stir to combine. Season to taste.

• In a medium bowl, combine mixed salad leaves, carrot and a drizzle of vinegar and olive oil. Season to taste.

• Divide beef borek filo snails and mixed green salad between plates.
• Serve with garlic yoghurt. Enjoy!